41
00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:25.510
All right. For a very long time, pathologists and clinicians have known

42
00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:28.800
that tumors change over time. They change phenotypically and

43
00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:32.380
morphologically. So there is a difference in a localized tumor,

44
00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:37.170
for example, in the skin in this case, and then something that starts becoming

45
00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:40.910
ugly looking, invading the surrounding tissue, metastasizing, and finally becoming

46
00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:44.800
resistant to treatment. But it is only relatively recently that,

47
00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:48.380
thanks to genomics, we have been able to map that these phenotypic

48
00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:51.780
morphological transformations are, in part,

49
00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.600
linked to specific genetic mutations.

50
00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:57.120
Some of them are genetic, some of them are not genetic.

51
00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:01.090
But if you take, in this case, for example, the colon epithelium, you can

52
00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:04.820
actually map that some of these transformations from normal epithelium to an early

53
00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:09.120
lesion are done through a mutation that knocks down APC,

54
00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:10.800
which is an important gene in

55
00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:15.740
controlling Wnt signaling in the epithelium of the colon.

56
00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:19.180
And then you have other mutations such as KRAS, SMARCA4, et cetera.

57
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.960
So there is, at least in part, genetic matching between the

58
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.200
transformation in the morphological level and the genetic level.

59
00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:31.080
And therefore, it has become evident in the last 20 years that

60
00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:35.020
this process behind this morphological and clinical

61
00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:38.840
change over time that drives this cancer

62
00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:41.380
progression is an evolutionary process.

63
00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:45.060
So the same fundamental rules and laws that drive the

64
00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:48.740
change in species also drive the change in

65
00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:51.920
cancer. So cells mutate, and they get selected, and

66
00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:56.300
they drive this change in population structure, and therefore,

67
00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:00.320
they make a cancer metastasize or become treatment resistant.

68
00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:04.320
So this is good news because we have a fundamental theory behind

69
00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:08.080
this complicated process that we can use. Okay.

70
00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:11.560
And the question that I try to tackle in my lab is, can we measure this process in

71
00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:14.280
humans, and can we predict it? Okay.

72
00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:17.680
Predicting evolution is an old question posed by Stephen Jay Gould, a famous

73
00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:19.320
evolutionary biologist in the '70s.

74
00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:23.840
If we roll back the tape of evolution, would we see the same organisms arising

75
00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:27.420
again, like bipedal mammals? This is a philosophical question, so people say, "Ah,

76
00:04:27.520 --> 00:04:27.600
no,

77
00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:32.500
evolution is contingent to random processes like an asteroid." Some other people

78
00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:34.660
said, "Well, there is a lot of convergence in evolution."

79
00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:38.910
If you look at whales and fish, they converge to the same

80
00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:42.200
physiological, biological structures like fins.

81
00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:46.120
So actually, evolution is predictable, and I try to convince you that indeed it is

82
00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.860
the case also in humans, where evolution did not happen only once, like in

83
00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:53.460
life, in the evolution of species, but it happens multiple times in different

84
00:04:53.560 --> 00:04:56.640
patients. There is recurrence. There is recurrence at the morphological level of

85
00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:00.160
cells, if you ask a pathologist. And there is a recurrent level of genetics, okay,

86
00:05:00.240 --> 00:05:02.260
with recurrent genetic mutations in driver genes.

87
00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:03.440
All right.

88
00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:09.060
So what do we want to measure? We have this complex diagram, okay, with all these

89
00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:11.760
clonal expansions and changes in population structure.

90
00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:14.180
You color the clones with different colors, et cetera.

91
00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:18.480
But what we want to measure in order to predict evolution in the future is

92
00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:22.180
things like positive selection. So identify what

93
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:25.760
clones are driven by some mutations or other heritable

94
00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:29.810
alterations that change the probability of surviving offspring with respect

95
00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:30.480
to the wild type.

96
00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:35.200
So positive selection increases the frequency of a certain

97
00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:35.760
mutant

98
00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:40.120
in the population over time. We want to discard

99
00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.960
mutations or at least model mutations that do not give you any change in

100
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:45.680
fitness. That's called neutral mutations.

101
00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:50.040
So in the case of observing mutations, because with genomics, we pick a

102
00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:52.480
lot of mutations, right? So we need to identify clones that

103
00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:57.420
have differential survival with respect to wild type clones or clones

104
00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:00.620
that drift around, okay? Because we need to model those in the data.

105
00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:04.440
The data contain this information, and we need to understand where is

106
00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:07.260
positive selection, where is neutrality, and where is negative selection, for

107
00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:09.560
example. Of course, there are clones that do not survive, okay?

108
00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:11.270
There are some lethal mutations in cancer.

109
00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:15.020
Or for example, they are predated by the immune system.

110
00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:18.320
So there is negative selection. So clean up by the immune system, certain

111
00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:20.990
immunogenic clones.All right, that's the idea.

112
00:06:21.490 --> 00:06:25.290
Now, the good news is that using evolutionary biology to understand

113
00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:29.030
cancer is also very useful because there is 100 years of

114
00:06:29.110 --> 00:06:30.050
maths behind.

115
00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:34.880
People for 120 years have been studying evolutionary

116
00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:38.920
biology in species with theoretical population genetics,

117
00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:43.230
which is the field of mathematics that married Darwin and Mendel.

118
00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:46.990
So the theory of heritability of Mendel with evolutionary biology by Darwin, which

119
00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:49.780
knew nothing about heritability, and everything he said about heritability was

120
00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:53.630
wrong. So there is great work by Wright, Fisher, Haldane

121
00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:58.790
in designing mathematical models for evolutionary problems.

122
00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:03.410
We can use this to study cancer evolution in the same way that we

123
00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:05.610
use this to study molecular evolution in humans.

124
00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:09.790
And they had the same questions. How does heritable variation spread in a

125
00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:13.290
population? What changes to mutant alleles? Et cetera.

126
00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:18.690
And some of the very first people that started using population genetics

127
00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:22.510
in cancer to understand their evolution are two of my mentors,

128
00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:26.250
Simon Tavare, who is my PhD supervisor, and Darrell Shibata at USC here in

129
00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:30.210
California. Back then, they used things like autoradiographs, which

130
00:07:30.670 --> 00:07:32.830
I have no idea what they are exactly, but you basically

131
00:07:33.990 --> 00:07:37.330
look at the length of microsatellites in cells to basically

132
00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:41.030
track their evolution in the same way that you look at tree

133
00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:43.570
rings in a tree trunk to understand what happened in the past.

134
00:07:44.420 --> 00:07:48.290
And they published papers back in the early 2000s, late '90s,

135
00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:52.530
on how we can use genetics to track, with molecular evolution

136
00:07:52.550 --> 00:07:55.650
approaches, colorectal cancer tumor histories, for example.

137
00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:59.430
So this is great stuff because they were doing cancer evolution way before it was

138
00:07:59.470 --> 00:08:00.010
cool.

139
00:08:01.670 --> 00:08:02.090
All right. So

140
00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:07.040
again, this is an educational session, so I'll give you an example of what you can

141
00:08:07.150 --> 00:08:11.090
do with evolutionary biology approaches based on population genetics with

142
00:08:11.110 --> 00:08:14.690
the most widely available data you can possibly find.

143
00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:16.310
So not fancy stuff, okay?

144
00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:21.030
Something like bulk genomic sequencing, where you take a tumor, you

145
00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:25.050
cut a chunk off, you mesh it up, and you sequence the genome of the cells inside

146
00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:28.930
many, many times. You get a long list of mutations, so differences between the

147
00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:31.810
genetics of the tumor and the baseline

148
00:08:31.970 --> 00:08:35.250
germline confirmation genome of the patient.

149
00:08:36.211 --> 00:08:37.571
Forget about what the mutations are.

150
00:08:38.230 --> 00:08:42.091
You look at the frequency of the mutations in this

151
00:08:42.191 --> 00:08:45.860
sample. They are little. So you'll have that some regions of the

152
00:08:45.910 --> 00:08:49.890
genomes have more coverage because maybe they have copy number alterations, and

153
00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:52.190
some of them have mutations in different alleles, et cetera.

154
00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:56.090
So what you can call is you can basically identify a variant allelic

155
00:08:56.230 --> 00:08:59.630
frequency of any given mutation. So you get coverage and you're getting some normal

156
00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:02.810
contamination, which is not mutated in the cancer because the cancer contains also

157
00:09:03.050 --> 00:09:05.090
normal cells and fibroblasts and other cells.

158
00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:09.450
Then you get the reads with the variant, then you take a ratio, and you calculate

159
00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:13.210
an allelic frequency, which is very important for methods based on evolutionary

160
00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:17.150
theory because we use this information, the distribution of allelic frequencies,

161
00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:18.590
to measure a lot of things.

162
00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:23.530
All right, this is a simple diagram where you have a normal cell here,

163
00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:26.230
and at some point, the normal cell

164
00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:30.040
acquires a certain driver mutation and expands, and another time.

165
00:09:30.070 --> 00:09:32.619
It's a very simple diagram. Very naive.

166
00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:38.130
But it already illustrates how you actually sample the data

167
00:09:38.170 --> 00:09:41.210
from a structure like this. The tumor is very big. You don't sample all the tumor.

168
00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:44.930
You take a biopsy or a piece of a resection, which is this gray thing over here.

169
00:09:45.310 --> 00:09:49.070
And then what you do is you look at the distribution of variant allelic

170
00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:52.550
frequencies of the mutations that you find here. So what will you expect to find?

171
00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:56.510
If it's a diploid tumor, doesn't happen very often, but let's assume it is, then

172
00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:59.050
a lot of mutations will be in one out of the two alleles.

173
00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:03.010
And if this is a pure tumor population, you expect a lot of mutations at

174
00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:06.990
50% allelic frequency. And you get a lot of

175
00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:10.790
overlapping mutations from different clones because some of them are these

176
00:10:10.830 --> 00:10:14.150
mutations in this stick over here, and some of them are these mutations after this

177
00:10:14.170 --> 00:10:15.970
driver, and some of them are these mutations.

178
00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:20.050
And then you also have some subclonal mutations, which I'll come back later to.

179
00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:22.830
So you can identify clonal mutations.

180
00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:25.420
At a lower frequency, you see subclonal mutations.

181
00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:28.260
So you have some information about intratumor heterogeneity.

182
00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:31.870
It's not like single cell, where you have really single cell

183
00:10:32.570 --> 00:10:35.850
identified genetic information. Here it's mixed up. You have bulk.

184
00:10:36.110 --> 00:10:39.270
But you have good statistics about intratumor heterogeneity because you pick a lot

185
00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:40.990
of mutations and a lot of cells.

186
00:10:43.070 --> 00:10:45.370
You have some confounding factors that many of you know.

187
00:10:45.490 --> 00:10:48.690
Of course, if you have normal contamination, the frequency of the alleles, the

188
00:10:48.750 --> 00:10:51.230
mutant alleles, are lower than you expect by chance.

189
00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:54.910
So instead of finding at 50% this cluster of mutations, you find them a bit

190
00:10:54.970 --> 00:10:58.750
lower. That's fine. In cancer, you have other confounding factors which are copy

191
00:10:58.810 --> 00:10:59.650
number alterations.

192
00:11:01.790 --> 00:11:03.790
Karyotypes in cancer can be altered.

193
00:11:03.819 --> 00:11:06.389
So sometimes you have three copies of a chromosome, four copies of a chromosome,

194
00:11:06.410 --> 00:11:09.900
one copy of a chromosome. So you get all these strange combinations of

195
00:11:09.910 --> 00:11:13.700
mutations where if you have a lot of mutations in one chromosome, you double that

196
00:11:13.730 --> 00:11:17.570
chromosome, then those mutations go higher in frequency, et cetera.

197
00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:21.600
But the whole point is this. We study evolution in the

198
00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:25.150
few methods that I'm going to discuss today using the frequency of the mutations

199
00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:28.460
you observe. These confounding factors, they change the frequency of these

200
00:11:28.490 --> 00:11:31.350
mutations. So you have to know that there are these confounding factors.

201
00:11:31.570 --> 00:11:35.330
These lower mutations, the frequency of mutations, normal contamination, and copy

202
00:11:35.370 --> 00:11:38.290
number alterations, they can lower or increase the frequency of this mutation.

203
00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:41.770
So you need to account for those. All right, that's fine.

204
00:11:41.830 --> 00:11:43.250
So okay, let's go back to the modeling.

205
00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:47.010
We want to model intratumor heterogeneity at the subclonal level

206
00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:49.810
with population genetics. So we can model random mutations.

207
00:11:49.830 --> 00:11:52.960
These are Poisson processes or accumulation of mutations. It's all statistics.

208
00:11:53.030 --> 00:11:57.010
We can do it. We can model genetic drift and non-random selection, arguably the

209
00:11:57.070 --> 00:11:59.330
most complicated thing to do in cancer.

210
00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:03.070
And this first part is about neutral dynamics, which is what we started with.

211
00:12:03.990 --> 00:12:06.590
More than 10 years ago, we said, "Okay, let's start with really simple maths."

212
00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:08.009
So

213
00:12:08.830 --> 00:12:12.230
if you start from that simple assumption that basically there are a few

214
00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:14.090
processes of random mutation,

215
00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:18.210
genetic drift, and non-random selection, you can model the cancer as a

216
00:12:18.230 --> 00:12:21.970
Luria-Delbrück experiment. The Luria-Delbrück experiment is the most important

217
00:12:22.030 --> 00:12:23.930
experiment in evolutionary biology ever done.

218
00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:27.650
It was worth a Nobel Prize, and it demonstrated for the first time

219
00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:31.350
experimentally that bacteria infected with viruses

220
00:12:31.770 --> 00:12:35.630
develop resistance to these viruses because of preexisting standing

221
00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:37.890
variation, which is positively selected.

222
00:12:37.930 --> 00:12:41.268
So in a Darwinian fashionOkay? And

223
00:12:42.218 --> 00:12:45.498
these two people, they proved it with a very clever experiment,

224
00:12:45.818 --> 00:12:49.718
where they seeded bacteria in different wells, and they look at the distribution

225
00:12:50.058 --> 00:12:51.958
of the frequencies of the mutants. Okay?

226
00:12:52.298 --> 00:12:54.338
And if all the mutants came from the same,

227
00:12:55.158 --> 00:12:58.598
let's say, hierarchy or a phylogenetic descendant of the wells,

228
00:12:58.758 --> 00:13:01.738
then the mutation is preexisting. Beautiful. Okay.

229
00:13:02.118 --> 00:13:05.878
Won the Nobel Prize in 1969, and that spawned a

230
00:13:05.938 --> 00:13:09.908
generation of models, mathematical models, to model exactly this

231
00:13:09.918 --> 00:13:13.418
process because everybody recognized this is a fundamental process in

232
00:13:13.458 --> 00:13:13.958
biology.

233
00:13:15.418 --> 00:13:18.898
The questions were the same. There are resistant mutants that happen, how they are

234
00:13:18.958 --> 00:13:21.428
selected, what is their frequency, et cetera.

235
00:13:21.748 --> 00:13:23.618
So in the cancer, we have the same questions.

236
00:13:23.658 --> 00:13:24.898
We start from a single cell,

237
00:13:25.818 --> 00:13:28.998
okay, and we model it as a Luria-Delbruck experiment, where there is a sexual

